        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has no documented chronic medical illness, prior psychiatric hospitalization, or previous suicide attempt, which are clinically plausible defaults because the provided evidence does not establish these features. The current episode is her first clearly recognized depressive episode, developing over several weeks with low mood, fatigue, anxiety, and impaired concentration [PMID:36156484, MEDDIALOG:F32.9:0].\n\nShe and her parents deny alcohol or illicit drug use, and there is no known recent head injury; this is relevant because psychiatric symptoms can be confused with other causes, but evidence suggests persistent depression may predate other acute events and need separate assessment [MEDDIALOG:F32.9:2]. She has regular menses and no amenorrhea, but endocrine screening is still reasonable because hyperprolactinemia has been associated with depressive symptoms in some patients [PMID:24182617].\n\n{patientName} is sleeping more than usual and has reduced appetite and motivation, which are clinically plausible neurovegetative symptoms consistent with depressive illness described in the evidence [PMID:36156484]. She has supportive parents and one close friend aware that she has been struggling. There have been no prior surgeries or major medical procedures."
          }
        ]
